from keras import backend as K
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator,load_img, img_to_array
from keras.models import Sequential, Model
from keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D,GlobalAveragePooling2D
from keras.layers import Activation, Dropout, BatchNormalization, Flatten, Dense, AvgPool2D,MaxPool2D
from keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16, preprocess_input
from keras.optimizers import Adam, SGD, RMSprop
import tensorflow as tf 
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing import image

# All Parameters of Conv2D:
#-------------------------------------------------------
#tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(
#    filters,
#    kernel_size,
#    strides=(1, 1),
#    padding="valid",
#    data_format=None,
#    dilation_rate=(1, 1),
#    groups=1,
#    activation=None,
#    use_bias=True,
#    kernel_initializer="glorot_uniform",
#    bias_initializer="zeros",
#    kernel_regularizer=None,
#    bias_regularizer=None,
#    activity_regularizer=None,
#    kernel_constraint=None,
#    bias_constraint=None,
#    **kwargs
#)
#-------------------------------------------------------

# All Parameters of MaxPooling2D:
#-------------------------------------------------------
#tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(
#    pool_size=(2, 2), strides=None, padding="valid", data_format=None, **kwargs
#)
#-------------------------------------------------------

model = Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), input_shape = INPUT_SHAPE, activation = "relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 48, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = "relu"))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2), strides = (1,1)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))

#fully connected
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(32, activation = "relu"))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(1, activation = "sigmoid"))

# compile 
model.compile(loss = "binary_crossentropy",
             optimizer = "rmsprop",
             metrics = ["accuracy"])

source.c85c0625: # Building CNN ## 1. Filters (Kernels) * Filters are tools for making convolution. We have an image and this image consists from pixels so an image actually is a matrix of values. For filters we create a matrix of values and then apply that filter onto image(applying dot product). The values on filter update in training, just like wights. * **Applying filter:** ![Convolution without zero(same) padding](https://eg.bucknell.edu/~cld028/courses/379-FA19/images/ConvEx.gif) * For a deeper understanding let me explain it more: Lets say we have a filter 3x3 and in the first row it filled with -1s, in the second **row** it filled with 2s and third row it filled with -1s again. This called a vertical line detector. So what if we want to make a horizontal line detector? Create a filter 3x3, fill first **column** with -1s, second columns with 2s and third column with -1s. * For more information: [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_detection) * **Horizontal line detector example(made with [GIMP](https://www.gimp.org/)):** * **How to do that in GIMP:** Open your **GIMP(version: 2.10.20)**, click on **"filters"**, click on **"generic"**, click on **"convolution matrix"**, after these steps you will see a 5x5 matrix. **This matrix is 5x5 but we will just use the 3x3 matrix in the middle**. Enter the the values for the horizontal line detector([-1,2,-1], [-1,2,-1], [-1,2,-1]) and click **"ok"**. * We learned what is a filter but as you can see in the first gif, we are losing information(our input is 5x5 but our output is 3x3). To solve that problem we use a technique called padding(we will learn zero(same) padding but there are different types of padding techniques). In zero padding we are drawing a frame that consists of zeros around the image. So with zero pedding we avoid from losing information. * **Zero padding:** ![Convolution](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/static.pyimagesearch.com/keras-conv2d/keras_conv2d_padding.gif) ## 2. Pools (Maxpooling) * Pooling is a technique that **speeds up the training process** and **prevents from overfitting.** * An image that represents **maxpooling**(stride = 2x2): ## 3. Fully Connected Part * Fully connected part consists from dense layers. Before this part we have to flatten the data. ## 4.ImageDataGenerator * In CNNs we need so much data but we cannot always find that much data. For training a CNN with small data and prevent from overfitting we are using **ImageDataGenerators**. ImageDataGenerator applies differences to an image. For example: It rotates image, changes brigthness, zoom in zoom out and more. * **Our model's diagram:**
